doc.after: The north faÃ§ade has three bays separated by windows and features a loggia, typical of early 17th-century houses, with a central arched entrance to accommodate coaches.[41] The central bay is crowned by an ornamental pierced parapet below a niched Dutch gable, which shelters a small statue of Lord Zouche[41][43] or James I.[44] There are small obelisks at either side of the gable.[29] Thorpe originally intended the main entrance of the house to be on this side, building on the gatehouse of the earlier Foxley house.[45]
